original_title: Brooklyn: New Lots Avenue - Schenck Avenue
text:
(1) New Lots Ave., south side, between Schenck Ave., and Hendrix Street, showing Mrs. M. Wortman's home.

About 1900.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) The same, showing S. Wortman's Blacksmith shop, (he was the son of Mrs. M. Wortman), which was opposite the Van Sickle farmhouse.

About 1900.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

original_title: Brooklyn: New Lots Avenue - Schenck Avenue
text:
New Lots Avenue, at the southeast corner of Schenck Avenue, showing the old Dutch Reformed New Lots Church.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  about 1900

original_title: Brooklyn: New Lots Avenue - Schenck Avenue
text:
New Lots Cemetery: New Lots Ave., south side, between Schenck Ave., and Jerome Street, showing Livonia Ave., in the background, with a B.M.T. Elevated station of the Fulton Street Line, and to the extreme left a rear section of P.S. No. 72. The cemetery partially seen in the foreground is no longer designated as such on the maps of 1929.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

original_title: Brooklyn: New Lots Avenue - Schenck Avenue
text:
(1) New Lots Ave., at the S.E. corner of Schenck Ave., showing from right to left the Parsonage, Sunday School, and church of the New Lots Church (Dutch Reformed). This church was dedicated in July 1824.

May 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) The same, viewed from Jerome Street. The cemetery is visible in the foreground.

May 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(3) The same, showing the church.

May 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
